{
  "text": "Abnormal BMI was significantly associated with MetS in IDF as well as NCEP-ATP criteria, and likewise several studies report illustrated that the BMI is a quantitative predictor of MetS [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Furthermore the level of education was directly associated with MetS. Similar findings have also been reported in urban India where the prevalence of MetS was significantly higher among study participants with level of education [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , and Alencastro et al. reported that education to be an independent predictor of MetS [CITATION_6] .",
